<section xml:id="sec_reciprocal_exponents">
  <title>Reciprocal Exponents</title>
  <introduction>
    <p><idx><m>n</m>-th root</idx> For a positive integer <m>n</m>, a real number <m>y</m> is an <term><m>n</m>-th root of <m>x</m></term> if <m>y^n=x</m>.</p>

    <p>If <m>n</m> is odd, every real number <m>x</m> has exactly one <m>n</m>-th root.</p>

    <p>If <m>n</m> is even, a real number <m>x</m> has no <m>n</m>-th root when <m>x\lt 0</m>, exactly one <m>n</m>-th root when <m>x=0</m>, and exactly two <m>n</m>-th roots when <m>x>0</m>.  If <m>x</m> has two <m>n</m>-th roots, one is positive and the other is its negative.</p>

    <p>The symbol <m>\sqrt[n]{x}</m> is defined to be the <m>n</m>-th root of <m>x</m> when <m>n</m> is odd, or the non-negative <m>n</m>-th root of <m>x</m>, if one exists, when <m>n</m> is even.</p>

    <p>Notice that if <m>n</m> is odd, <m>\sqrt[n]{x}</m> exists and has the same sign as <m>x</m>.</p>

    <example>
      <title>Some examples of Roots</title>
      <statement>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <m>\sqrt[3]{64} = 4</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>\sqrt[3]{-64} = -4</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>\sqrt[2]{64} = 8</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>-\sqrt[2]{64} = (-1) \sqrt[2]{64} =-8</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>\sqrt[2]{-64} \text{ is not defined. }</m>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>The expression <m>x^\frac{1}{n}</m> is just another way of writing <m>\sqrt[n]{x}</m>.  Notice that if <m>x^\frac{1}{n}</m> is defined, then <m>\left(x^\frac{1}{n}\right)^n=x</m>.</p>
    
    <p>If <m>n</m> is even and <m>x</m> is non-negative, then <m>(x^n)^\frac{1}{n} = x</m>, because <m>x^n</m> is non-negative and <m>(x^n)^\frac{1}{n}</m> is the non-negative <m>n</m>-th root of <m>x^n</m>.  If <m>n</m> is even and <m>x</m> is negative, then <m>x^n</m> is positive, so that <m>(x^n)^\frac{1}{n}=\mid x \mid</m>.</p>
    
    <p>For example <m>((-3)^2)^\frac{1}{2}= 9^\frac{1}{2}=3</m>.  Notice that, in this case, the expression <m>\left((-3)^\frac{1}{2}\right)^2</m> does not make sense because <m>(-3)^\frac{1}{2}</m> is not defined.</p>

    <p>When <m>n</m> is odd, <m>x^n</m> has the same sign as <m>x</m>, so that <m>(x^n)^\frac{1}{n}</m> also has the same sign as <m>x</m>.  Therefore <m>(x^n)^\frac{1}{n}=x</m>.  For example <m>((-3)^3)^{\frac{1}{3}} = (-27)^{\frac{1}{3}}=-3</m> and, since <m>(-3)^{\frac{1}{3}}</m> is defined, <m>\left((-3)^\frac{1}{3}\right)^3=-3</m>.</p>

    <example>
      <title>Finding an <m>n</m>-th root</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Find <m>x</m> if <m>x^\frac{1}{4} = \frac{3}{2}</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>Since <m>x^\frac{1}{4} = \frac{3}{2}</m>, we know that</p>
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}
            x &amp;= \left(x^\frac{1}{4}\right)^4 \\
            &amp;= \left(\frac{3}{2}\right)^4 \\
            &amp;= \frac{3^4}{2^4} \\
            &amp;= \frac{81}{16}
          \end{aligned}
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>
    
    <example>
      <title>Finding another <m>n</m>-th root</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Find <m>x</m> if <m>x^\frac{1}{3} = \left(\frac{5}{4}\right)^\frac{1}{7}</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>Since <m>x^\frac{1}{3} = \left(\frac{5}{4}\right)^\frac{1}{7}</m>, we know that</p>
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}
            x &amp;= \left(x^\frac{1}{3}\right)^{3} \\
            &amp;= \left(\left(\frac{5}{4}\right)^\frac{1}{7}\right)^{3} \\
            &amp;= \left(\sqrt[7]{\frac{5}{4}}\right)^{3} \\
            &amp;= \sqrt[7]{\frac{125}{64}}
          \end{aligned}
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </introduction>
  <exercises>
    <title>Practice Problems</title>
    <statement>
      <p>In questions 1 - 5, use the rules of exponents to find an expression equivalent to given expression.</p>
    </statement>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <m>36^\frac{1}{2}</m>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <m>6</m>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <m>(-125)^\frac{1}{3}</m>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <m>-5</m>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <m>(\frac{9}{4})^\frac{1}{2}</m>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <m>\frac{3}{2}</m>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <m>x^\frac{1}{4}x^{-\frac{1}{5}}</m>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <m>x^\frac{1}{20}</m>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <m>(m^\frac{1}{2}n^{-\frac{1}{3}})^{-\frac{1}{6}}</m>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <m>\frac{ n^{1/18}} { m^{1/12}}</m>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>Find <m>x</m> if <m>x^\frac{1}{5} = \left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^\frac{1}{2}</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <m>\sqrt{\frac{32}{243}} = \frac{4}{9}\sqrt{\frac{2}{3}}</m>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  </exercises>
</section>
